<subSubSection id="C337088DF77DB13DB182F8CC374243BB" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="530" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B925B06F77DB13DB182F8CC374243BB" blockId="8.[151,1437,1375,2013]" lastBlockId="9.[151,1437,150,249]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="530" pageId="8" pageNumber="529">
COMMENTS: See 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC26F7F77DB13CB03EF8CC30AC440F" author="Gyldenstolpe, N." box="[379,661,1843,1869]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" pagination="1 - 116" refId="ref28755" refString="Gyldenstolpe, N. (1926) Types of birds in the Royal Natural History Museum in Stockholm. Arkiv f or Zoologi, 19, 1 - 116." type="journal article" year="1926">Gyldenstolpe (1926: 83</bibRefCitation>
, 115) for discussion of the name. The 
<typeStatus id="5496E5A4F77DB13CB51EF8CC36B7440F" box="[1115,1166,1843,1869]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529">type</typeStatus>
locality, Magalies Berg (which is unjustified)proposed by Gyldenstolpe needs correction, and should be Hartebeespoort. On p. 68 of the translation of Wahlberg’s journal (
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC26F7F77DB13CB366F884310144D7" author="Craig, A. &amp; Hummel, C." box="[547,824,1915,1941]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" refId="ref28290" refString="Craig, A. &amp; Hummel, C. (1994) Johan August Wahlberg. Travel Journals (and Some Letters) South Africa and Namibia / Botswana, 1838 - 1856. Translated from Swedish by Michael Roberts. Series 2. No. 23. Van Riebeeck Society, Cape Town, 249 pp." type="book" year="1994">Craig &amp; Hummel 1994</bibRefCitation>
), he noted that on 
<date id="FF937DC6F77DB13CB548F88536D644D7" box="[1037,1263,1914,1941]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" value="1841-11-15">15 November 1841</date>
he travelled to the Crocodile River and from there past “Makhalies Berg’s Poort” (= Hartebeespoort) to camp at an unnamed river, moving closer to the river the next day (see 
<figureCitation id="13164783F77DB13CB39CF83C3105449F" box="[729,828,1987,2013]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1113,1137]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1088]" captionTargetId="figure-19@17.[151,1436,179,1088]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 3. Wahlberg’s camps and collecting sites (red dots) in the North West Province 1842–1844." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6541743" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6541743/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="529">Figure 3</figureCitation>
). His meeting with Burke and Zeyher (see introduction) on 15 November (according to Wahlberg’s journal) or 17 November (according to Burke’s journal) suggests that his camp was close to Hartebeespoort. Wahlberg made no further mention of travel until 
<date id="FF937DC6F77CB13DB46FFF4432EC43BB" pageId="9" pageNumber="530" value="1842-01-08">8 January 1842</date>
, so it can be assumed that he camped in more or less the same place from 15 November to 5 January.
</paragraph>
